{
  "texts": [
    "It relies on one-hot encoding, which is insufficient for capturing rich semantic information and leads to sparse representation.",
    "Furthermore, it treats the essay as a sequence of words, overlooking the hierarchical word, sentence, and paragraph levels in the actual document structure of the essay.",
    "Several research works have proposed solutions to address these limitations, while others have extended this work to enhance scoring accuracy in AES models.",
    "In Table 2, we present a summary of neural network-based prompt-specific holistic scoring papers, with many of them being extensions of this work.",
    "Introducing semantics using word embeddings: Alikaniotis et al. (2016) proposed using C &W word embeddings for essay representation instead of one-hot encoding to capture score-specific word senses and dependencies."
  ]
}